  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'A Song of Heavenly Mandate: With Preface'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the autumn of the eighteenth year of Hongwu, on the seventh month, the Son of Heaven sat in court and issued an edict establishing our lord as king, and bestowing upon our late sovereign the posthumous name Gongmin. In the ninth month, envoys arrived bearing the royal charter and edict of appointment, all composed by the Son of Heaven himself. Our lord, clothed in the ceremonial robes of his predecessor, led his ministers in full regalia to receive them at the city gates. Three times he bowed and cried ten thousand years. On an auspicious day, we burned the imperial proclamation and made offerings at the ancestral temple, following the rituals sent down from the imperial court. The officials then addressed their lord, saying: "We unworthy servants, favored beyond measure by our late king, have guarded his throne for twelve years, trembling as if suspended between heaven and earth. Now that you have taken your rightful place and our former king has received his name, the realm is at peace and all celebrate together. Truly this is the restoration of our three kingdoms. Unless we carve these merits in stone and proclaim them to ten thousand ages, we cannot honor the Son of Heaven's grace. Therefore we humbly request that you command Yi Saek to compose this tribute." The edict granted their request. When the new year arrived, the high ministers proposed: "There is no better time than this to establish a Song of Heavenly Mandate." Thus was I commanded to write.

    I reflect that our Great Ancestor received the Mandate in his twenty-second year, and since then each successor has received confirmation from the Middle Kingdom. The grace shown to our small nation and the etiquette of serving the great power are beyond what other tributary states dare aspire to. When Yuan's twilight came, our late king, perceiving the turn of fortune, crossed the sea to present tribute—truly Heaven's will. Now our sovereign, inheriting his father's intent and maintaining his policies, grows ever more reverent. His sincerity reaches heaven and earth. The Son of Heaven's bright command descends from on high, allowing our small realm to preserve our customs and maintain our laws. His care is deep, his instruction profound. How can I not present this song?

    *The Song:*

    Our eastern realm, throughout the ages,
    Has cherished the ways of civilization.
    From the Five Dynasties through Yuan's fall,
    The Emperor's favor ever deepened.

    Our late king received this charge—
    Ah, how perilous those days!
    When all turned northward,
    Only we journeyed south.

    Brilliant is the Great Ming!
    It perceived our sincerity.
    Long was the path to trust,
    Yet investiture came at last.

    The edict's words, grave and deep,
    Flow from the Emperor's heart.
    Standing above all ages past,
    It illuminates this present day.

    The imperial instruction shines before us—
    Do not dare to rest in ease,
    Fearing not mere earthly power,
    But the majesty of Heaven itself.

    Fulfill your sacred duty without fail,
    Diligent in governance, kind to your people.
    Respond to the times and heed their signs.
    So the Emperor commends with satisfaction.

    He does not cast us far away—
    Above and below, without divide,
    Our state shall endure in order.

    Yet should we stray from this path,
    Heaven's will becomes obscure.
    Let all who hold position ponder
    The meaning of this song.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gongmin (恭愍) was the posthumous name given to King Gongmin of Goryeo by the Ming court. This edict marked the formal recognition of the new Goryeo leadership by the Ming Dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: The preface documents the official ceremonies and rituals surrounding the investiture, reflecting the careful political choreography required to maintain tributary relations while preserving internal legitimacy.
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Saek's reference to the 'Great Ancestor' receiving the Mandate in his twenty-second year alludes to Goryeo's founding mythology and its claim to continuous legitimate rule.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Five Dynasties' (오계) refers to the fragmented period in Chinese history before the Song Dynasty, emphasizing the continuity of Goryeo's tributary relationship across centuries of Chinese political upheaval.
